## 🏗️ Types of Client-Server Architecture

### 1-Tier (All in One)

- Client + Server + Database on the **same machine**
- Example: A simple desktop app like Notepad or a local database tool
- **Use case:** Small standalone apps, prototyping

### 2-Tier (Client + Server)

- Client talks **directly** to the server
- Server handles both business logic AND database
- Example: A contact form that saves directly to a database
- **Use case:** Simple apps with a single database

### 3-Tier (Most Common! ⭐)

- **Presentation Layer** → What the user sees (Client/UI)
- **Application Layer** → Business logic and processing (App Server)
- **Data Layer** → Where all the data lives (Database)
- Example: Instagram, Amazon, Netflix, nearly all modern web apps
- **Use case:** Most production applications

> **3-Tier is the standard for modern applications.** It separates concerns, making each layer independently scalable and maintainable.

## ⚔️ Client vs Server — Quick Comparison

|Aspect       |Client                  |Server                           |
|-------------|------------------------|---------------------------------|
|**Role**     |Requests data           |Responds with data               |
|**Location** |User’s device           |Data center / Cloud              |
|**Examples** |Browser, mobile app     |Node.js, Django, Spring Boot     |
|**Initiates**|Communication           |Waiting for requests             |
|**Count**    |Many (millions of users)|Few (can be just one, or scaled) |
|**Resources**|Limited (phone, laptop) |Powerful (high CPU, RAM, storage)|

## 💡 Key Takeaways

1. **Client asks, Server answers** — this is the core pattern
1. They communicate via **Request & Response**
1. Most modern apps use **3-Tier Architecture** (Client → App Server → Database)
1. This pattern scales to **millions of users**
1. Client-Server is the **foundation** of the entire internet

